                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>On the 29th of October the prisoner came into my house and had a pint of beer; it being a wet night she dried herself for an hour and half by the fire; then she took an opportunity to pour part of the water out of the tea-kettle into the ashes; she paid for her beer and went away; the tea-kettle was missed by my servant; I pursued the prisoner and took her with it under her apron.</p>
               <p>'The prisoner in her defence pleaded poverty</p>
               <p>'and great distress.'</p>
               <p>Prosecutor. She was in a very distressed situation.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17761204-21-verdict108" type="verdictDescription">
